```cpp
#include <hexi/static_buffer.h>

template<size_t buffer_size = 1024>
struct BufferInfo {
    size_t capacity;
    size_t current_size;
    size_t free_space;
};

BufferInfo<> get_buffer_info(const hexi::static_buffer<std::byte, 1024>& buffer) {
    BufferInfo<> info;

    // Total capacity is fixed by the template parameter
    info.capacity = 1024;

    // Current readable data size is the difference between write and read pointers
    // This handles both linear and wrapped buffer scenarios
    info.current_size = buffer.size();

    // Free space is capacity minus current size
    info.free_space = info.capacity - info.current_size;

    return info;
}
```

However, looking more closely at the `static_buffer` implementation pattern from the code fragments, I notice that it uses `read_` and `write_` member variables. Let me provide a more precise implementation that directly accesses these members:

