#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

struct TypedData {
    uint32_t id;
    int16_t value;
    double ratio;
};

std::vector<uint8_t> write_typed_data(const TypedData& data) {
    std::vector<uint8_t> buffer;
    hexi::pmc::buffer_write_adaptor adaptor(buffer);

    // Write each field in sequence using template write method
    adaptor.write(data.id);
    adaptor.write(data.value);
    adaptor.write(data.ratio);

    return buffer;
}

TypedData read_typed_data(const std::vector<uint8_t>& buffer) {
    TypedData data;
    hexi::pmc::buffer_read_adaptor adaptor(buffer);

    // Read each field in the same order they were written
    adaptor.read(&data.id);
    adaptor.read(&data.value);
    adaptor.read(&data.ratio);

    return data;
}
```

The implementation uses Hexi's buffer adaptors to provide type-safe read/write operations:

- `buffer_write_adaptor` wraps the vector and provides template `write()` methods that handle the correct byte size and endianness for each type
- `buffer_read_adaptor` similarly provides template `read()` methods that read the exact number of bytes needed for each type
- The order of operations is preserved between writing and reading
- The adaptors automatically handle the buffer management and positioning

This ensures type safety while maintaining the sequential nature of the binary data stream.

